respond, they will reintroduce the Registration Act.

79
00:12:02,012 --> 00:12:09,269
The president could declare a state of emergency,
place every mutant in the country under arrest.

80
00:12:09,352 --> 00:12:14,691
- Do you think the assassin is working alone?
- Probably we will only know that if we find him before the authorities do.

81
00:12:14,775 --> 00:12:21,406
I've been trying to track him using Cerebro,
but his movements are inexplicably erratic.

82
00:12:21,490 --> 00:12:27,036
When I have exact coordinates, Storm, Jean,
I'll need you to take the jet and try pick him up.

83
00:12:29,622 --> 00:12:32,583
It was close, wasn't it?

84
00:12:32,666 --> 00:12:35,378
Closer than anyone's admitted.

85
00:12:35,461 --> 00:12:41,550
- What do you need, William?
- Just your authorisation for a special operation.

86
00:12:41,634 --> 00:12:44,428
No, thank you, Mr President.

87
00:12:44,512 --> 00:12:47,348
And somehow I thought you were here
to talk about school reform.

88
00:12:47,431 --> 00:12:49,767
Funny you should say that, Mr President.

89
00:12:50,726 --> 00:12:54,521
- Senator.
- Mr President. Thank you for having me.

90
00:12:54,604 --> 00:12:58,900
- Senator Kelly, this is Colonel William Stryker.
- How do you do?

91
00:12:58,983 --> 00:13:03,446
His department has been dealing with the
mutant phenomenon since... before my time.

92
00:13:03,530 --> 00:13:06,699
As I recall, you were a staunch supporter
of the Registration Act, Senator.

93
00:13:06,783 --> 00:13:10,245
But it seems your ideas on
the mutant problem have changed recently.

94
00:13:10,328 --> 00:13:15,166
So what are you proposing, Mr Stryker?

95
00:13:15,250 --> 00:13:17,585
May I, Mr President?

96
00:13:30,556 --> 00:13:34,518
We've managed to gather evidence
of a mutant training facility

97
00:13:34,601 --> 00:13:38,188
in the Salem region of upstate New York.

98
00:13:38,272 --> 00:13:40,399
Where did you get this information?

99
00:13:40,482 --> 00:13:45,821
Interrogation of one of the mutant terrorists
from the Liberty Island incident.

100
00:13:45,904 --> 00:13:50,241
- Eric? Eric Lehnsherr? - You have access to him?
- Magneto, yes.

101
00:13:50,324 --> 00:13:55,663
We developed the technology
that built his plastic prison.

102
00:13:57,457 --> 00:14:01,377
- This facility is a school.
- Sure it is.

103
00:14:05,048 --> 00:14:07,300
- What the hell is that?
- A jet.

104
00:14:07,383 --> 00:14:10,553
- What kind of jet?
- We don't know.

105
00:14:11,512 --> 00:14:15,223
But it comes up out of the basketball court.

106
00:14:21,271 --> 00:14:24,608
If we'd been allowed to do our jobs,
Mr President, before this incident...

107
00:14:24,691 --> 00:14:27,027
All right, listen.

108
00:14:30,197 --> 00:14:33,450
William, you enter, you detain, you question,

109
00:14:33,533 --> 00:14:39,997
but the last thing we need to see is the body
of a mutant kid on the six o'clock news.

110
00:14:47,338 --> 00:14:49,715
- Mr Stryker?
- Senator Kelly.

111
00:14:51,133 --> 00:14:54,303
This is Yuriko, my personal assistant.

112
00:14:54,387 --> 00:14:57,014
- Quite a handshake.
- What can I do for you?

113
00:14:57,098 --> 00:15:00,518
Uh, Eric Lehnsherr's prison.
I'd like to arrange a visit if possible.

114
00:15:00,601 --> 00:15:02,770
It isn't a petting zoo, Senator.

115
00:15:02,853 --> 00:15:07,774
In this conflict he is the enemy, you're just a
spectator, so why don't you sit this one out, all right?

116
00:15:07,857 --> 00:15:13,738
Mr Stryker, do you really
want to turn this into some kind of war?

117
00:15:17,409 --> 00:15:20,453
I was piloting black ops missions
in the jungles of north Vietnam

118
00:15:20,537 --> 00:15:23,957
while you were sucking on
your mama's tit at Woodstock, Kelly.

119
00:15:24,040 --> 00:15:27,961
Don't lecture me about war.
This already is a war.

120
00:15:38,345 --> 00:15:41,932
- You're dead. You're so dead.
- You're dead.

121
00:15:47,146 --> 00:15:49,481
I don't wanna hurt you.

122
00:15:51,150 --> 00:15:53,027
I'm not afraid.

123
00:16:11,627 --> 00:16:13,629
Logan.

124
00:16:15,089 --> 00:16:17,050
You miss me, kid?

125
00:16:17,133 --> 00:16:18,801
Not really.

126
00:16:18,885 --> 00:16:21,345
- How are you doing?
- I'm OK. How are you?

127
00:16:21,429 --> 00:16:23,389
- Who's this?
- This is Bobby. He's my...

128
00:16:23,473 --> 00:16:25,475
I'm her boyfriend.

129
00:16:25,558 --> 00:16:27,976
Call me Iceman.

130
00:16:31,229 --> 00:16:32,981
Right.

131
00:16:33,065 --> 00:16:36,902
Boyfriend? So how do you guys...?

132
00:16:36,985 --> 00:16:39,154
Well, we're still working on that.

133
00:16:39,237 --> 00:16:42,991
Look who's come back. Just in time.

134
00:16:43,075 --> 00:16:45,035
For what?

135
00:16:45,118 --> 00:16:48,163
- We need a baby-sitter.
- Baby-sitter?

136
00:16:48,246 --> 00:16:49,915
Nice to see you again, Logan.

137
00:16:50,665 --> 00:16:52,792
Hi, Logan.

138
00:16:53,584 --> 00:16:55,294
Hi, Jean.

139
00:16:55,378 --> 00:16:58,214
Uh, I should go and get the jet ready.

140
00:16:58,297 --> 00:17:00,841
Yeah, well, it's good to meet you.

141
00:17:00,925 --> 00:17:04,512
- Come on, let's go.
- Bye, Logan. I'll see you later.

142
00:17:10,684 --> 00:17:13,771
Storm and I are heading to Boston.
We won't be gone long.

143
00:17:13,854 --> 00:17:17,441
The professor wants us to track down
a mutant who attacked the President.

144
00:17:17,525 --> 00:17:19,484
So it was a mutant.

145
00:17:19,567 --> 00:17:25,615
You'll be here when we get back,
unless you plan on running off again.

146
00:17:25,699 --> 00:17:30,286
Well, I could probably think of
a few reasons to stick around.

147
00:17:30,370 --> 00:17:33,456
Find what you were looking for, Logan?

148
00:17:33,540 --> 00:17:35,417
More or less.

149
00:17:35,500 --> 00:17:38,128
I'll see you boys later.

150
00:17:38,211 --> 00:17:41,506
- Be safe, OK?
- You too. Bye.

151
00:17:41,589 --> 00:17:43,591
See ya.

152
00:17:45,884 --> 00:17:48,887
Aren't you gonna welcome me home?

153
00:17:49,471 --> 00:17:52,099
Your bike needs gas.

154
00:17:52,182 --> 00:17:54,184
Then fill her up.

155
00:18:09,199 --> 00:18:11,201


156
00:18:13,870 --> 00:18:17,457
Mr Laurio, how long can we keep this up?

157
00:18:19,917 --> 00:18:23,004
- How long is your sentence?
- Forever.

158
00:18:23,087 --> 00:18:28,259
Not necessarily forever, Mr Lehnsherr.
Just until I've got all that I need.

159
00:18:28,342 --> 00:18:31,429
Mr Stryker, how kind of you to visit.

160
00:18:31,512 --> 00:18:37,977
Have you come back to ensure the taxpayers'
